Sensitivity analysis - Model with synthesised effect sizes for various correlation sizes

#combine effect sizes with different correlation sizes

compute_rma <- function(cor, Study, Cor, N, Data) {
  d <- MAc::agg(id = Study, r = Cor, n = N, cor = cor, mod=NULL, data = Data)
  d <- escalc(measure = "ZCOR", ri = r, ni = n, data = d)
  rma(yi, vi, data= d, measure="OR", method="REML")
}

results = list()
for (cor in  seq(.1, 1,.2))  {
    results[[as.character(cor)]] = compute_rma(cor, Study, Cor, N, Data)
  }

print(results)

Eggerâs regression test/ PET-PEESE procedure

#Tests for bias
regtest(res) # PET
## 
## Regression Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry
## 
## Model:     mixed-effects meta-regression model
## Predictor: standard error
## 
## Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry: z = -1.4146, p = 0.1572
## Limit Estimate (as sei -> 0):   b = 0.1978 (CI: 0.0257, 0.3699)
regtest(res, predictor="vi") # PEESE
## 
## Regression Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry
## 
## Model:     mixed-effects meta-regression model
## Predictor: sampling variance
## 
## Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry: z = -1.3938, p = 0.1634
## Limit Estimate (as vi -> 0):    b = 0.1359 (CI: 0.0396, 0.2323)

Rank correlation test

#Tests for bias
ranktest(res, exact = FALSE)
## 
## Rank Correlation Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry
## 
## Kendall's tau = -0.0706, p = 0.5290

Both ranktest and Eggerâs regression test do not test directly for publication bias. Instead, they indicate whether thereâs evidence that the funnel plot is asymmetric, which may occur due to publication bias, but not exclusively. According to these results thereâs no evidence that there is plot asymmetry.

Outlier/influential points detection

par("mar")
## [1] 5.1 4.1 4.1 2.1
### calculate influence diagnostics
inf <- influence(res)
 
### plot the influence diagnostics
plot(inf)

Neither Eggerâs regression test (p = .192) or the Rank correlation test (p = .838) was statistically significant so thereâs no evidence of publication bias according to these tests. Study 27 is identified as outlier/influential

Sensitivity analysis - Model with synthesised effect sizes

#combine effect sizes with different correlation sizes

compute_rma <- function(cor, Study, Cor, N, Data) {
  d <- MAc::agg(id = Study, r = Cor, n = N, cor = cor, mod=NULL, data = Data_language)
  d <- escalc(measure = "ZCOR", ri = r, ni = n, data = d)
  rma(yi, vi, data= d, measure="OR", method="REML")
}

results = list()
for (cor in  seq(.1, 1,.2))  {
    results[[as.character(cor)]] = compute_rma(cor, Study, Cor, N, Data)
  }

print(results)

Sensitivity analysis - Model with synthesised effect sizes for various correlation sizes

#combine effect sizes with different correlation sizes

compute_rma <- function(cor, Study, Cor, N, Data) {
  d <- MAc::agg(id = Study, r = Cor, n = N, cor = cor, mod=NULL, data = Data_literacy)
  d <- escalc(measure = "ZCOR", ri = r, ni = n, data = d)
  rma(yi, vi, data= d, measure="OR", method="REML")
}

results = list()
for (cor in  seq(.1, 1,.2)) {
    results[[as.character(cor)]] = compute_rma(cor, Study, Cor, N, Data)
  }

print(results)

spelling.model <- robu(formula = yi ~ 0 + Group, data = Data_spelling[Data_spelling$Group != 'DLD',],
                       studynum = Study, var.eff.size = vi,
                       rho = .8, small = TRUE)

print(spelling.model)
